1 D. The State Regents shall implement policies and procedures
2 for the administration of this act. The State Regents shall approve
3 as eligible institutions of higher education only those private or
4 independent, not-for-profit colleges or universities that are
5 domiciled within this state, meet approved program and accreditation
6 standards as determined by the State Regents, and are fully
7 accredited by the Higher Learning Commission of the North Central
8 Association on Colleges and Schools or a national accrediting body
9 recognized by the United States Department of Education. To be
10 eligible, institutions must have been granted not-for-profit status
11 by the Internal Revenue Service and the U. S. Department of
12 Education prior to July 1, 2012. Additionally, eligible
13 institutions shall adhere to the complaint process policies and
14 procedures administered by the State Regents. The State Regents
15 shall review and take action, as authorized, on complaints
16 concerning eligible institutions. The eligible institutions shall
17 include Bacone College, Family of Faith College, Mid-America
18 Christian University, Oklahoma Baptist University, Oklahoma
19 Christian University, Oklahoma City University, Oklahoma Wesleyan
20 University, Oral Roberts University, Southern Nazarene University,
21 Southwestern Christian University, St. Gregory's University, the
22 University of Tulsa and Randall University.
23 E. If funds are not sufficient in the Oklahoma Tuition
24 Equalization Grant Trust Fund to provide grants for all eligible
ENGR. H. B. NO. 2888 Page 3

1 appl icants, the State Regents shall award grants on the basis of
2 need and take into consideration other grants and scholarships
3 received by an eligible applicant when awarding grants. Students
4 who have previously received a tuition equalization grant and who
5 continue to meet the requirements for eligibility shall have
6 absolute priority for continued financial support superior to any
7 student who is applying for a grant for the first time.
8 F. Students enrolling as first-time freshmen for the 2003-2004
9 school year shall be the first class of students eligible to apply
10 for Oklahoma Tuition Equalization Grants. In subsequent years, all
11 previously eligible students and the first-time enrolling freshmen
12 students shall be entitled to apply for a grant pursuant to this
13 section. Beginning in the 2007-2008 school year, all eligible
14 students shall be entitled to apply for a grant pursuant to this
15 section.
16 G. A grant provided by this section shall not be allowed for
17 courses or other postsecondary units taken in excess of the
18 requirements for completion of a baccalaureate program or taken more
19 than five (5) years after the student's first grant is received.
20 The State Regents may award an Oklahoma Tuition Equalization Grant
21 for courses of postsecondary units taken more than five (5) years
22 after the student's first grant is received only in hardship
23 circumstances. No Oklahoma Tuition Equalization Grant recipient may
24 receive benefits beyond a cumulative time period of five (5) years.
